To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Nevada Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

For the period January 1, 2019 through the date this request is processed,

 1. Adult Protective Services aggregate data and logs

Records sufficient to show, by calendar year:

the number of Adult Protective Services reports involving adults in community-based, residential, group-home, board-and-care, assisted-living, provider-operated, HCBS, or other noninstitutional congregate settings;
allegation type, including abuse, neglect, self-neglect, exploitation, isolation, abandonment, sexual abuse, physical abuse, emotional abuse, medication-related neglect, restraint, seclusion, unexplained injury, hospitalization, death, elopement, theft, or similar tracked categories;
referral source;
county;
whether the report was screened in or screened out;
whether an investigation was opened;
disposition or finding category, including substantiated, unsubstantiated, inconclusive, unable to determine, or similar terms used by the agency;
whether the matter was referred to HCQC, Nevada Medicaid, law enforcement, the Nevada Attorney General, or another agency;
average and median time to assignment and closure, if tracked.

I also request any de-identified case logs or incident logs sufficient to show the above information on a case-level basis, excluding personal identifiers of alleged victims.

2. APS policies, manuals, and referral guidance

All policies, manuals, training materials, desk procedures, decision trees, or written guidance concerning:

intake and screening of APS reports involving licensed or provider-operated community placements;
substantiation standards;
referral requirements to HCQC, Nevada Medicaid, law enforcement, or the Nevada Attorney General;
closure criteria for APS cases involving community placements.

3. HCQC complaint, investigation, and deficiency records

Records sufficient to show all complaints, investigations, findings, citations, deficiencies, and enforcement actions from January 1, 2019 to present for adult residential/community care settings serving adults with disabilities, mental illness, intellectual/developmental disabilities, or other vulnerable adults, including but not limited to residential facilities for groups, assisted-living facilities, board-and-care settings, and similar licensed congregate care settings.

Specifically, I request records sufficient to show:

facility/provider name;
license number;
facility type;
county;
complaint intake date;
allegation category;
complaint priority level;
investigation opening date;
investigation closing date;
disposition, including substantiated or not substantiated if tracked;
citation or deficiency number, if any;
sanctions or enforcement action, if any.

4. HCQC underlying enforcement materials

All statements of deficiencies, notices of violation, plans of correction, sanction notices, provisional licensure records, suspension records, revocation records, denial-of-renewal records, occupancy limitation records, or other adverse licensure records issued in response to complaints involving abuse, neglect, exploitation, resident injury, medication error, restraint, seclusion, resident-rights violations, unexplained injuries, elopement, hospitalization, or death.

5. HCQC complaint-intake and triage guidance

All complaint-intake manuals, triage criteria, prioritization guidance, training materials, and investigative workflow records used to assess and process complaints involving the settings described above.

6. Nevada Medicaid incident-reporting, serious-occurrence, and critical-incident oversight

All policies, manuals, provider bulletins, guidance documents, training materials, reporting instructions, desk procedures, and oversight records concerning:

critical incident reporting;
serious occurrence reporting;
reporting of abuse, neglect, exploitation, restraint, seclusion, medication errors, elopement, hospitalization, serious injury, and death;
reporting obligations of Medicaid providers, managed care organizations, subcontractors, or waiver providers in community residential or HCBS settings.

7. Nevada Medicaid incident data and provider oversight

Any aggregate reports, dashboards, spreadsheets, summaries, quarterly reports, annual reports, or other records sufficient to show critical incidents or serious occurrences reported to Nevada Medicaid, or reported by providers or managed care organizations to Nevada Medicaid, concerning:

abuse;
neglect;
exploitation;
medication errors;
restraints or seclusion;
injuries;
hospitalizations;
deaths;
elopements;
law-enforcement referrals;
corrective actions imposed on providers.

I also request any records sufficient to show provider sanctions, payment holds, terminations, exclusions, denied revalidations, overpayment findings, corrective action plans, focused reviews, audits, or compliance reviews involving Medicaid-funded residential/community providers during the requested period.

8. HCBS settings compliance records

All records concerning Nevada’s implementation, monitoring, or enforcement of HCBS settings requirements for residential or provider-operated settings, including:

site-review tools;
compliance review tools;
assessment forms;
transition-plan materials;
corrective action plans;
findings of noncompliance;
records concerning privacy, dignity, autonomy, visitor restrictions, curfews, food access, phone access, roommate choice, community access, locked doors, alarms, coercive medication practices, restraint, or seclusion.

9. Cross-agency referral and coordination records

Any memoranda of understanding, referral protocols, desk procedures, written guidance, meeting agendas, meeting minutes, slide decks, dashboards, or summaries governing or discussing coordination between or among:

APS;
HCQC;
Nevada Medicaid;
local law enforcement;
the Nevada Attorney General or Medicaid Fraud Control Unit.

This includes records sufficient to show:

outgoing referrals made by DHS divisions concerning abuse, neglect, exploitation, or serious incidents in community placements;
incoming referrals received by DHS divisions from other agencies concerning the same;
reason for referral;
receiving agency;
disposition or resolution category, if tracked.

10. Staffing, backlog, and capacity records

Any records sufficient to show staffing levels, vacancy rates, average caseloads, backlog metrics, or capacity concerns affecting APS, HCQC complaint investigations, or DHS/Medicaid oversight of abuse and neglect allegations in community placements.

11. Top providers / facilities

Records sufficient to show the providers or facilities with the highest number of complaints, substantiated complaints, citations, critical incidents, serious occurrences, or repeated allegations involving abuse, neglect, exploitation, medication errors, restraint, unexplained injuries, or deaths during the requested period.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

David Cutie

